";; appendix-04-nina-simone.slat
;; Book of Music — Appendix 4: Nina Simone — The Uncategorizable
;; Written 2026-07-13. Author: Lacuna Labs Engineering.
;; Real subject: Eunice Kathleen Waymon / Nina Simone (1933-2003).
;; Sources: Alan Light, What Happened, Miss Simone? (Crown Archetype, 2016);
;; Nadine Cohodas, Princess Noire: The Tumultuous Reign of Nina Simone
;; (Pantheon, 2010); Simone's own I Put a Spell on You: The Autobiography of
;; Nina Simone (Da Capo, 1991).

(appendix
  :book \"book-of-music\"
  :number 4
  :title \"Nina Simone — The Uncategorizable\"
  :short-title \"nina-simone\"
  :estimated-words 1800
  :subject-verified \"Nina Simone (born Eunice Kathleen Waymon, 21 February 1933, Tryon, North Carolina; died 21 April 2003, Carry-le-Rouet, France). Pianist, singer, composer, arranger.\"
  :philosopher-weave (aristotle wittgenstein-late peirce jung)

  :prose
\"Nina Simone wanted to be a classical concert pianist. She played Bach and Beethoven from the age of three or four, was recognized as a prodigy in her small North Carolina town, and was sent to the Juilliard School for a summer of study in preparation for an audition at the Curtis Institute of Music in Philadelphia. She auditioned at Curtis in 1950 and was not admitted. She always believed the rejection was due to race — a Black woman applying to an elite conservatory in 1950 — and while this cannot be verified with certainty, the biographies (Cohodas, Light) note that Simone herself never doubted it and that Curtis's admissions records from that era do not survive to settle the question either way.

She needed to make money, and she was a pianist, so she took a job at an Atlantic City nightclub called the Midtown Bar. The owner told her she would also have to sing, or he wouldn't hire her. She sang. She had a low, warm, unusual voice — a contralto with the timbre of a viola. She played piano and she sang and she made up her own arrangements. She combined classical piano technique (which nobody in the room could believe was happening in a nightclub) with jazz phrasing (which she had learned by ear) with a repertoire that spanned show tunes, blues, folk, and spirituals. She became famous almost by accident.

Over her career, she was called a jazz singer, a soul singer, a folk singer, a protest singer, a chanson singer, a gospel singer, and a classical pianist. She rejected most of these labels. She preferred to describe her music as 'Black classical music.' Whatever we call it, it does not fit inside any of the categories the record industry knew how to sell.

# Why she matters for the book

We have spent this book building a vocabulary — pitch, harmony, form, rubato, texture, style. Nina Simone is a case study in what happens when a musician learns that vocabulary deeply from one tradition (Western classical) and then applies it, unashamedly and without dilution, to material from other traditions.

Her recording of 'I Loves You, Porgy' (from Gershwin's *Porgy and Bess*, 1959, Bethlehem Records) is the first thing she released that got national attention. The vocal phrasing is jazz — she leans behind the beat, uses vibrato only at the ends of long notes, articulates each word. The piano playing underneath — mostly her own — is fully classical. Voice-leading is careful, harmonies use tenths in the left hand, and the intros between vocal phrases have the character of a Chopin nocturne interlude. The two styles do not fight. They interlock because the same person is doing both, and she doesn't feel a stylistic contradiction.

Her recording of 'Mississippi Goddam' (1964, Philips Records) is the opposite direction. She wrote the song after the September 1963 bombing of the 16th Street Baptist Church in Birmingham that killed four Black girls, and the assassination in June of that year of the civil rights leader Medgar Evers. The song is a protest song, marked as a show tune ('This is a show tune, but the show hasn't been written for it yet,' she says in the live introduction on the *Nina Simone in Concert* album), but sung with rage. The piano is stride piano — the left hand jumping between bass notes and mid-register chords, a swing feel driving the whole thing. The rage is heard through the cheerful surface, which is part of the song's design. She said later she found the form of a show tune the most cutting way to say what she meant.

Her recording of 'I Put a Spell on You' (1965, Philips) takes the Screamin' Jay Hawkins 1956 R&B song and remakes it. She slows it. She adds strings — a full orchestral arrangement by Hal Mooney. Her voice is deep, controlled, threatening. What was a novelty song in Hawkins' recording becomes, in her hands, a psychological study.

# The technique — piano voicings under her voice

If you listen to Nina Simone's piano playing under her own voice — which you can do on nearly any of her recordings, because she almost always played her own piano — you notice something that is not standard jazz piano.

Standard jazz piano, in the mid-twentieth century, used *rootless voicings* in the left hand — the pianist would play the third and seventh (or seventh and ninth) of each chord in the left hand, and the bassist would play the root. This freed the left hand to play more complex color notes and interact with the harmony.

Simone was often her own bassist. She played the root in the left hand, low, and she played the chord in the middle register with the same care a classical pianist would use to voice a Bach four-part chorale. Her voicings are *full*. The chords rest on their roots, they are supported by inner voices that move by careful step, and she uses passing tones and suspensions that come out of Bach and Chopin rather than out of jazz voicings.

This is why her ballads sound so *thick* — the bass is grounded, the chords are dense, the voice sits above a full harmonic bed. It is also why her uptempo pieces have a particular character — the left hand has to do the work of both bass and lower chord voices, which produces a stride-like feel even in songs that aren't stride pieces.

# What we can do in Scheme

Let's build a small demonstration of a Simone-style voicing under a vocal line.

```scheme
;; A ballad texture: root in the low left hand, chord in the middle,
;; melody in the right hand top voice.
;; C major 7 to A minor 7 to D minor 7 to G7 — a standard progression.

(define (simone-voicing root chord-type)
  (case chord-type
    ((maj7) (list root (transpose root 12) (transpose root 16) (transpose root 19) (transpose root 23)))
    ((min7) (list root (transpose root 12) (transpose root 15) (transpose root 19) (transpose root 22)))
    ((dom7) (list root (transpose root 12) (transpose root 16) (transpose root 19) (transpose root 22)))))

(define ballad-progression
  '((C3 maj7)   ; C major 7
    (A2 min7)   ; A minor 7
    (D3 min7)   ; D minor 7
    (G2 dom7))) ; G dominant 7

(define melody
  '((E5 half) (D5 half) (C5 half) (D5 half)))

(define (play-ballad-bar chord-info note-info)
  (let* ((root (car chord-info))
         (type (cadr chord-info))
         (voicing (simone-voicing root type)))
    (with-dynamics 'mp
      (pedal/press)
      (parallel
        (chord/play voicing 'whole)
        (list (note-play (car note-info) (cadr note-info))))
      (pedal/release))))

(transport/tempo 60)
(for-each play-ballad-bar ballad-progression melody)
```

The program is a fragment — four bars, one chord per bar, one melody note per bar. What it shows is the *voicing shape*: root in the deep bass (C3, A2, D3, G2), then the chord tones stacked up over four octaves, then the melody note on top. This is very different from a standard jazz voicing (which would leave the root to a bass player) and closer to a classical piano voicing (which would fill in the whole harmonic space with the piano alone).

# What her career teaches

Nina Simone was rejected by Curtis Institute in 1950 — an event she carried her whole life. She did not become the classical pianist she wanted to be. She became, instead, an artist whose refusal to fit any category was so complete that a whole generation of musicians who came after her (Alicia Keys, Lauryn Hill, Solange, and many others have named her as an influence) had a new possibility opened up: that a pianist who was trained in Bach could sing about civil rights and play stride and record with strings and refuse to be labeled, and could reach an enormous audience by *not* pretending to be one specific thing.

For a book that is trying to teach music to a reader who does not yet know what kind of musician they are, Simone is important. She is proof that mastering a tradition does not commit you to staying inside it. Learn the harmony deeply, learn the phrasing carefully, learn the form clearly — and then use them for whatever material you have to say. The mastery does not disappear when the material changes; it lets the new material be said with more precision.

# Recommended listening

'I Loves You, Porgy' — the 1959 Bethlehem recording. Her first hit.

'Sinnerman' — from *Pastel Blues* (1965, Philips). A ten-minute traditional spiritual arrangement that shows her at full extension.

'Mississippi Goddam' — from *Nina Simone in Concert* (1964, Philips). Recorded live at Carnegie Hall.

'I Put a Spell on You' — from *I Put a Spell on You* (1965, Philips). The arrangement is by Hal Mooney.

'Ne Me Quitte Pas' — from *I Put a Spell on You* (1965). A Jacques Brel song, sung in French, showing her chanson dimension.

# Sources cited

Alan Light, *What Happened, Miss Simone?* (Crown Archetype, 2016). The companion book to Liz Garbus's documentary.

Nadine Cohodas, *Princess Noire: The Tumultuous Reign of Nina Simone* (Pantheon, 2010).

Nina Simone with Stephen Cleary, *I Put a Spell on You: The Autobiography of Nina Simone* (Da Capo, 1991).

Discography reference: allmusic.com Nina Simone entry, and the Philips Records archive.\"

  :notes
\"Biographical facts (birth 1933, Curtis audition 1950, career trajectory) are consistent across the three biographies cited. The Curtis rejection is documented in Simone's autobiography and both biographies; the racism interpretation is Simone's own view. Song release dates are verified in the Philips/Bethlehem discographies. The 1963 events referenced in 'Mississippi Goddam' (16th Street Baptist Church bombing 15 September; Medgar Evers assassination 12 June) are historical. The interpretation of her piano voicings is based on transcriptions and audio analysis; it is a scholarly-level interpretation, not a documented Simone-authorized description.\"

  :philosopher-weave-details
\"Aristotle: an artist who learned one form (classical piano) and used it to shape another form (protest song, ballad, spiritual) — the form of the action carries across the material.
Wittgenstein-late: her music as a language-game none of the existing labels could contain — she made a new form-of-life for a musician.
Peirce: her recordings as index of a specific person at a specific moment — the way her voice sits behind the beat is a physical trace of who she was.
Jung: her uncategorizability as an integration of parts (classical training + jazz phrasing + protest content + folk material + chanson delivery) — a self that would not be split.\"

  :tie-forward
\"Appendix 5 will pull the harmonic thread further — the blues progression, its variations, and why it works.\")
")
